			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2010</a> paper:</span><br><i>Support for the Evolution of C++ Generic Functions</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/PeterPirkelbauer.html">Peter Pirkelbauer</a>, <a href="../profile/DamianDechev.html">Damian Dechev</a>, <a href="../profile/BjarneStroustrup.html">Bjarne Stroustrup</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-19440-5_8">10.1007/978-3-642-19440-5_8</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagM">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> The paper addresses language feature evolution/maintenance for C++ generic functions across language/library change.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3d.html"><span class="tagL">T3D: GPLs</span></a><ul><li> It is rooted in a general-purpose programming language (C++) and its evolution support.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> The work discusses integration of language mechanisms with existing C++ code and tooling constraints.
</li></ul></li></ul>
